  <title>Recording Audio</title>

  <p>Learn how to record audio onto your tracks.</p>

  <section id="basic-recording">
    <title>Recording on a Track</title>
    <steps>
      <item><p>Make sure you have a track to record on. Add one with 
      <keyseq><key>Ctrl</key><key>T</key></keyseq> if needed.</p></item>
      <item><p>Click the <gui style="button">üî¥</gui> (record) button on the track.</p></item>
      <item><p>The track status changes to "Recording‚Ä¶" with a red highlight.</p></item>
      <item><p>Speak or play your audio.</p></item>
      <item><p>Click the <gui style="button">‚èπ</gui> (stop) button to finish.</p></item>
    </steps>
  </section>

  <section id="recording-tips">
    <title>Recording Tips</title>
    <list>
      <item>
        <p><em style="strong">Check your input:</em> Use input monitoring 
        (<keyseq><key>Ctrl</key><key>L</key></keyseq>) to hear your microphone 
        before recording.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p><em style="strong">One track at a time:</em> Only one track can 
        record at a time.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p><em style="strong">Recordings replace:</em> Recording on a track 
        that already has audio will replace the previous recording.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p><em style="strong">Audio format:</em> All recordings are saved 
        as WAV files for maximum quality.</p>
      </item>
    </list>
  </section>

  <section id="monitoring">
    <title>Input Monitoring</title>
    <p>Input monitoring lets you hear your microphone in real-time:</p>
    <list>
      <item><p>Click the <gui style="button">üîä</gui> button in the header bar, or</p></item>
      <item><p>Press <keyseq><key>Ctrl</key><key>L</key></keyseq></p></item>
    </list>
    <p>This is useful for:</p>
    <list>
      <item><p>Checking microphone levels before recording</p></item>
      <item><p>Monitoring your voice while recording</p></item>
      <item><p>Testing audio input settings</p></item>
    </list>
    <note style="tip">
      <p>Monitoring uses PipeWire's low-latency audio path for minimal delay.</p>
    </note>
  </section>

